examples: If he was at fault at all, it must have been some unconscious misjudgment, mistake, or mismove in manipulating the brake or in applying the reverse current, not disclosed by the evidence. Such misjudgment, mismove, or mistake [...]

verbs.description: mismove (third-person singular simple present mismoves, present participle mismoving, simple past and past participle mismoved)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To move wrongly, incorrectly, or in error.
examples: Good morra, Willie," says he, with the same old vicious smile. "Good morra and good luck," says Willie, as little as ever mismoved, "won't ye sit down and have a pick of dinner with us?"

entries.meaning: (transitive, UK dialectal, Northern England) To disturb; trouble; to disconcert; alarm; flurry.
